{{good article}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Spinal cord injury | synonyms = | image = Cervical Spine MRI (T2W).jpg | caption = [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] of fractured and dislocated neck vertebra that is [[Spinal cord compression|compressing the spinal cord]] | pronounce = | field = [[Neurosurgery]] | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = Complete, incomplete<ref name=ATLS2018/> | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = Based on symptoms, [[medical imaging]]<ref name=ATLS2018/> | differential = | prevention = | treatment = [[Spinal motion restriction]], [[intravenous fluids]], [[vasopressors]]<ref name=ATLS2018/> | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = c. 12,000 per year (USA)<ref name=NS2012>{{cite web|title=Spinal Cord Injury Facts and Figures at a Glance|url=https://www.nscisc.uab.edu/PublicDocuments/fact_figures_docs/Facts%202012%20Feb%20Final.pdf|accessdate=16 May 2018|date=2012}}</ref> | deaths = }} <!-- Definition and symptoms --> A '''spinal cord injury''' ('''SCI''') is damage to the [[spinal cord]] that causes temporary or permanent changes in its function. Symptoms may include loss of muscle function, [[sensory system|sensation]], or [[autonomic nervous system|autonomic]] function in the parts of the body served by the spinal cord below the level of the injury. Injury can occur at any level of the spinal cord and can be ''complete injury'', with a total loss of sensation and muscle function, or ''incomplete'', meaning some nervous signals are able to travel past the injured area of the cord. Depending on the location and severity of damage, the symptoms vary, from numbness to [[paralysis]] to [[bladder incontinence|incontinence]]. Long term outcomes also ranges widely, from full recovery to permanent [[tetraplegia]] (also called quadriplegia) or [[paraplegia]]. Complications can include [[muscle atrophy]], [[pressure sore]]s, infections, and breathing problems.
<!-- Cause and diagnosis --> In the majority of cases the damage results from [[physical trauma]] such as car accidents, gunshots, falls, or sports injuries, but it can also result from nontraumatic causes such as infection, insufficient blood flow, and tumors. Just over half of injuries affect the [[cervical spine]], while 15% occur in each of the [[thoracic spine]], border between the thoracic and [[lumbar spine]], and lumbar spine.<ref name=ATLS2018>{{cite book|title=ATLS - Advanced Trauma Life Support - Student Course Manual|date=2018|publisher=American College of Surgeons|isbn=78-0-9968262-3-5|pages=129–144|edition= 10th}}</ref> Diagnosis is typically based on symptoms and [[medical imaging]].<ref name=ATLS2018/>
<!-- Prevention and treatment --> Efforts to prevent SCI include individual measures such as using safety equipment, societal measures such as safety regulations in sports and traffic, and improvements to equipment. Treatment starts with [[spinal motion restriction|restricting further motion of the spine]] and maintaining adequate [[blood pressure]].<ref name=ATLS2018/> [[Corticosteroids]] have not been found to be useful.<ref name=ATLS2018/> Other interventions vary depending on the location and extent of the injury, from bed rest to surgery. In many cases, spinal cord injuries require long-term [[physical therapy|physical]] and [[occupational therapy]], especially if it interferes with [[activities of daily living]].
<!-- Epidemiology, history, and culture --> In the United States, about 12,000 people a year survive with a spinal cord injury.<ref name=NS2012/> The most commonly affected group are young adult males.<ref name=NS2012/> SCI has seen great improvements in its care since the middle of the 20th century. Research into potential treatments includes [[stem cell]] implantation, engineered materials for tissue support, epidural spinal stimulation, and wearable [[powered exoskeleton|robotic exoskeleton]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Krucoff|first=Max O.|last2=Rahimpour|first2=Shervin|last3=Slutzky|first3=Marc W.|last4=Edgerton|first4=V. Reggie|last5=Turner|first5=Dennis A.|date=2016-12-27|year=|title=Enhancing Nervous System Recovery through Neurobiologics, Neural Interface Training, and Neurorehabilitation|journal=Frontiers in Neuroscience|volume=10|pages=584|doi=10.3389/fnins.2016.00584|issn=1662-4548|pmc=5186786|pmid=28082858}}</ref>
==Classification== {| width="260px" style="text-align: center; margin-left: 15px; float:right;" |- | style="border-bottom:0px;" |[[File:Gray 111 - Vertebral column-coloured labels.png|90px|alt=A human spinal column]] | style="border-bottom:0px;" |[[File:Dermatoms alt.svg|182px|alt=A person with dermatomes mapped out on the skin]] |- | style="border-top:0px;" colspan="2"|The effects of injury depend on the level along the [[spinal column]] (left). A [[dermatome (anatomy)|dermatome]] is an area of the skin that sends sensory messages to a specific spinal nerve (right). |- | style="border-top:0px;" colspan="2"|[[File:ACDF oblique annotated english.svg|260px|alt=diagram of vertebrae and spinal nerves]] |- | style="border-top:0px;" colspan="2"|Spinal nerves exit the spinal cord between each pair of vertebrae. |} Spinal cord injury can be [[major trauma|traumatic]] or nontraumatic,<ref name="Sabapathy15"/> and can be classified into three types based on cause: mechanical forces, toxic, and [[ischemia|ischemic]] (from lack of blood flow).{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}} The damage can also be divided into [[primary and secondary injury]]: the cell death that occurs immediately in the original injury, and [[biochemical cascade]]s that are initiated by the original insult and cause further tissue damage.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=335}} These secondary injury pathways include the [[ischemic cascade]], [[inflammation]], [[edema|swelling]], [[apoptosis|cell suicide]], and [[neurotransmitter]] imbalances.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=335}} They can take place for minutes or weeks following the injury.<ref name="Yu15"/>
At each level of the spinal column, [[spinal nerve]]s branch off from either side of the spinal cord and exit between a pair of [[vertebra]]e, to innervate a specific part of the body. The area of skin innervated by a specific spinal nerve is called a [[dermatome (anatomy)|dermatome]], and the group of muscles innervated by a single spinal nerve is called a [[myotome]]. The part of the spinal cord that was damaged corresponds to the spinal nerves at that level and below. Injuries can be cervical 1–8 (C1–C8), thoracic 1–12 (T1–T12), lumbar 1–5 (L1–L5),{{sfn|Cifu|Lew|2013|p=197}} or sacral (S1–S5).<ref name="NINDS13"/> A person's level of injury is defined as the lowest level of full sensation and function.{{sfn|Miller|Marini|2012|p=138}} Paraplegia occurs when the legs are affected by the spinal cord damage (in thoracic, lumbar, or sacral injuries), and tetraplegia occurs when all four limbs are affected (cervical damage).{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=5}}
SCI is also classified by the degree of impairment. The ''International Standards for Neurological Classification of Spinal Cord Injury'' (ISNCSCI), published by the [[American Spinal Injury Association]] (ASIA), is widely used to document sensory and motor impairments following SCI.<ref name=Marino/> It is based on neurological responses, touch and pinprick sensations tested in each dermatome, and strength of the muscles that control key motions on both sides of the body.<ref name="ISCOS"/> Muscle strength is scored on a scale of 0–5 according to the table on the right, and sensation is graded on a scale of 0–2: 0 is no sensation, 1 is altered or decreased sensation, and 2 is full sensation.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=307}} Each side of the body is graded independently.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=307}}
{| class="wikitable" style="width: 100%; float: right;" !colspan="2" style="text-align:center;background-color:#ffc0c0;"|Muscle strength{{sfn|Harvey|2008|p=7}} !colspan="2" style="text-align:center;background-color:lightblue;"|ASIA Impairment Scale for classifying spinal cord injury<ref name="ISCOS"/>{{sfn|Teufack|Harrop|Ashwini|2012|p=67}} |- ! style="text-align:center;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Grade ! style="text-align:center;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Muscle function ! style="text-align:center;background-color:lightblue;" | Grade ! style="text-align:center;background-color:lightblue;" | Description |- ! 0 |No muscle contraction !<!--col1-->A |<!--col2-->'''Complete injury'''. No motor or sensory function is preserved in the sacral segments S4 or S5. |- ! 1 | Muscle flickers !B |'''Sensory incomplete'''. Sensory but not motor function is preserved below the level of injury, including the sacral segments. |- ! 2 | Full range of motion, gravity eliminated !C |'''Motor incomplete'''. Motor function is preserved below the level of injury, and more than half of muscles tested below the level of injury have a muscle grade less than 3 (see muscle strength scores, left). |- ! 3 | Full range of motion, against gravity ! D |'''Motor incomplete'''. Motor function is preserved below the level of injury and at least half of the key muscles below the neurological level have a muscle grade of 3 or more. |- ! 4 | Full range of motion against resistance !E |'''Normal'''. No motor or sensory deficits, but deficits existed in the past. |- ! 5 | Normal strength ! | |} {{clear}}
===Complete and incomplete injuries=== {| class="wikitable" style="float: right; margin-left:15px; text-align: center;" |+ Level and completeness of injuries{{sfn|Field-Fote|pp=7–8}} | ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Complete ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Incomplete |- ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;"|Tetraplegia |18.3% |34.1% |- ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;"|Paraplegia |23.0% |18.5% |} In a "complete" spinal injury, all functions below the injured area are lost, whether or not the spinal cord is severed.<ref name="NINDS13"/> An "incomplete" spinal cord injury involves preservation of motor or sensory function below the level of injury in the spinal cord.<ref name="SCI Medicine"/> To be classed as incomplete, there must be some preservation of sensation or motion in the areas innervated by S4 to S5,{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=840}} e.g. voluntary [[external anal sphincter]] contraction.<ref name="SCI Medicine"/> The nerves in this area are connected to the very lowest region of the spinal cord, and retaining sensation and function in these parts of the body indicates that the spinal cord is only partially damaged. Incomplete injury by definition includes a phenomenon known as sacral sparing: some degree of sensation is preserved in the sacral dermatomes, even though sensation may be more impaired in other, higher dermatomes below the level of the lesion.<ref name="Lafuente85"/> Sacral sparing has been attributed to the fact that the sacral spinal pathways are not as likely as the other spinal pathways to become compressed after injury due to the lamination of fibers within the spinal cord.<ref name="Lafuente85" />
===Spinal cord injury without radiographic abnormality=== [[Spinal cord injury without radiographic abnormality]] exists when SCI is present but there is no evidence of spinal column injury on [[radiograph]]s.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=288}} [[Vertebral column|Spinal column injury]] is trauma that causes [[bone fracture|fracture]] of the bone or instability of the [[denticulate ligaments|ligaments]] in the [[spinal column|spine]]; this can coexist with or cause injury to the spinal cord, but each injury can occur without the other.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|pp=288–89}} Abnormalities might show up on [[magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI), but the term was coined before MRI was in common use.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=289}}
===Central cord syndrome=== [[File:Cord s.svg|thumb|right|Incomplete lesions of the spinal cord: Central cord syndrome&nbsp;(top), Anterior cord syndrome&nbsp;(middle), and Brown-Séquard syndrome&nbsp;(bottom).]] [[Central cord syndrome]], almost always resulting from damage to the cervical spinal cord, is characterized by weakness in the arms with relative sparing of the legs, and spared sensation in regions served by the sacral segments.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}} There is loss of sensation of pain, temperature, light touch, and pressure below the level of injury.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=170}} The spinal tracts that serve the arms are more affected due to their central location in the spinal cord, while the corticospinal fibers destined for the legs are spared due to their more external location.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=170}} The most common of the incomplete SCI syndromes, central cord syndrome usually results from neck [[hyperextension]] in older people with spinal [[stenosis]]. In younger people, it most commonly results from neck flexion.{{sfn|Namdari|Pill|Mehta|2014|p=297}} The most common causes are falls and vehicle accidents; however other possible causes include [[spinal stenosis]] and impingement on the spinal cord by a tumor or vertebral disk.{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1420}}
===Anterior cord syndrome=== [[Anterior cord syndrome]], due to damage to the front portion of the spinal cord or reduction in the blood supply from the [[anterior spinal artery]], can be caused by fractures or dislocations of vertebrae or herniated disks.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=170}} Below the level of injury, motor function, pain sensation, and temperature sensation are lost, while sense of touch and [[proprioception]] (sense of position in space) remain intact.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=9}}{{sfn|Namdari|Pill|Mehta|2014|p=297}} These differences are due to the relative locations of the spinal tracts responsible for each type of function.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=170}}
===Brown-Séquard syndrome=== [[Brown-Séquard syndrome]] occurs when the spinal cord is injured on one side much more than the other.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}} It is rare for the spinal cord to be truly hemisected (severed on one side), but partial lesions due to penetrating wounds (such as gunshot or knife wounds) or fractured vertebrae or tumors are common.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=171}} On the ipsilateral side of the injury (same side), the body loses motor function, [[proprioception]], and senses of vibration and touch.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}} On the contralateral (opposite side) of the injury, there is a loss of pain and temperature sensations.{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1420}}{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}}
===Posterior cord syndrome=== [[Posterior cord syndrome]], in which just the [[dorsal column]]s of the spinal cord are affected, is usually seen in cases of chronic [[myelopathy]] but can also occur with infarction of the [[posterior spinal artery]].{{sfn|Roos|2012|pp=249–50}} This rare syndrome causes the loss of proprioception and sense of vibration below the level of injury{{sfn|Namdari|Pill|Mehta|2014|p=297}} while motor function and sensation of pain, temperature, and touch remain intact.{{sfn|Ilyas|Rehman|2013|p=389}} Usually posterior cord injuries result from insults like disease or vitamin deficiency rather than trauma.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=294}} [[Tabes dorsalis]], due to injury to the posterior part of the spinal cord caused by syphilis, results in loss of touch and proprioceptive sensation.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=167}}
===Conus medullaris and cauda equina syndromes=== [[Conus medullaris]] syndrome is an injury to the end of the spinal cord, located at about the T12–L2 vertebrae in adults.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}} This region contains the S4–S5 spinal segments, responsible for bowel, bladder, and some [[sexual function]]s, so these can be disrupted in this type of injury.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}} In addition, sensation and the [[Achilles reflex]] can be disrupted.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=10}} Causes include [[neoplasm|tumors]], physical trauma, and [[ischemia]].{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1422}}
[[Cauda equina syndrome]] (CES) results from a lesion below the level at which the spinal cord splits into the [[cauda equina]],{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=294}} at levels L2–S5 below the conus medullaris.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=11}} Thus it is not a true spinal cord syndrome since it is nerve roots that are damaged and not the cord itself; however it is common for several of these nerves to be damaged at the same time due to their proximity.{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1422}} CES can occur by itself or alongside conus medullaris syndrome.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=11}} It can cause low back pain, weakness or paralysis in the lower limbs, loss of sensation, bowel and bladder dysfunction, and loss of reflexes.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=11}} Unlike in conus medullaris syndrome, symptoms often occur on only one side of the body.{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1422}} The cause is often compression, e.g. by a ruptured intervertebral disk or tumor.{{sfn|Marx|Walls|Hockberger|2013|p=1422}} Since the nerves damaged in CES are actually [[peripheral nerve]]s because they have already branched off from the spinal cord, the injury has better prognosis for recovery of function: the [[peripheral nervous system]] has a greater capacity for healing than the [[central nervous system]].{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=11}}
==Signs and symptoms== {|class="wikitable floatright" style="width:300px;" |+'''Actions of the [[spinal nerve]]s''' ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" width="75px" | Level ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Motor Function |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 1|C1]]–[[cervical spinal nerve 6|C6]] |Neck [[flexor]]s |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 1|C1]]–[[thoracic spinal nerve 1|T1]] |Neck [[extensor]]s |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 3|C3]], [[cervical spinal nerve 4|C4]], [[cervical spinal nerve 5|C5]] |Supply [[diaphragm (anatomy)|diaphragm]] (mostly [[cervical spinal nerve 4|C4]]) |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 5|C5]], [[cervical spinal nerve 6|C6]] |Move [[shoulder]], raise [[arm]] ([[deltoid muscle|deltoid]]); flex elbow ([[biceps]]) |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 6|C6]] | externally rotate ([[supinate]]) the arm |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 6|C6]], [[cervical spinal nerve 7|C7]] |[[Extension (kinesiology)|Extend]] [[Elbow-joint|elbow]] and [[wrist]] ([[triceps brachii muscle|triceps]] and wrist [[extensor]]s); [[pronate]] wrist |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[cervical spinal nerve 7|C7]], [[thoracic spinal nerve 1|T1]] |Flex wrist; supply small muscles of the [[hand]] |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[thoracic spinal nerve 1|T1]]–[[thoracic spinal nerve 6|T6]] |[[Intercostal muscle|Intercostal]]s and [[torso|trunk]] above the [[waist]] |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[thoracic spinal nerve 7|T7]]–[[lumbar spinal nerve 1|L1]] |[[Abdomen|Abdominal]] muscles |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[lumbar spinal nerve 1|L1]]–[[lumbar spinal nerve 4|L4]] |Flex [[thigh]] |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[lumbar spinal nerve 2|L2]], [[lumbar spinal nerve 3|L3]], [[lumbar spinal nerve 4|L4]] | [[adduction|Adduct]] thigh; Extend [[human leg|leg]] at the [[knee]] ([[quadriceps femoris]]) |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[lumbar spinal nerve 4|L4]], [[lumbar spinal nerve 5|L5]], [[sacral spinal nerve 1|S1]] |[[Abduction (kinesiology)|abduct]] thigh; Flex leg at the knee ([[hamstring]]s); [[Dorsiflexion|Dorsiflex]] [[foot]] ([[tibialis anterior]]); Extend [[toe]]s |- ! style="text-align:left;" | [[lumbar spinal nerve 5|L5]], [[sacral spinal nerve 1|S1]], [[sacral spinal nerve 2|S2]] |Extend leg at the [[hip]] ([[gluteus maximus]]); [[Plantar]] flex foot and flex toes |- |}
{{Further|Dermatome (anatomy)}} [[Medical sign|Signs]] (observed by a clinician) and [[symptom]]s (experienced by a patient) vary depending on where the spine is injured and the extent of the injury. <!--SENSATION--> A section of skin [[nerve|innervated]] through a specific part of the spine is called a [[dermatome (anatomy)|dermatome]], and injury to that part of the spine can cause pain, numbness, or a loss of sensation in the related areas. [[Paraesthesia]], a tingling or burning sensation in affected areas of the skin, is another symptom.{{sfn|Augustine|2011|p=199}} A person with a lowered [[level of consciousness]] may show a response to a painful stimulus above a certain point but not below it.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=39}} <!--MUSCLE FUNCTION--> A group of muscles innervated through a specific part of the spine is called a [[myotome]], and injury to that part of the spinal cord can cause problems with movements that involve those muscles. The muscles may contract uncontrollably ([[spasticity]]), become [[paresis|weak]], or be completely [[paralysis|paralysed]]. [[Spinal shock]], loss of neural activity including reflexes below the level of injury, occurs shortly after the injury and usually goes away within a day.{{sfn|Snell|2010|p=169}}
The specific parts of the body affected by loss of function are determined by the level of injury.
===Lumbosacral=== The effects of injuries at or above the [[lumbar]] or [[sacrum|sacral]] regions of the spinal cord (lower back and pelvis) include decreased control of the [[human leg|legs]] and [[hip]]s, [[genitourinary system]], and anus. People injured below level L2 may still have use of their hip flexor and knee extensor muscles.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=313}} [[intestine|Bowel]] and [[urinary bladder|bladder]] function are regulated by the [[sacrum|sacral]] region. It is common to experience [[sexuality after spinal cord injury|sexual dysfunction after injury]], as well as dysfunction of the bowel and bladder, including [[fecal incontinence|fecal]] and [[urinary incontinence]].<ref name="NINDS13"/> It is also possible for the bladder to fail to empty,{{sfn|Fulk|Behrman|Schmitz|2013|p=898}} leading to a potentially harmful buildup of urine.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=314}} One sign of spinal cord injury that emergency providers may find is [[priapism]], an [[erection]] of the penis.{{sfn|Augustine|2011|p=200}}
===Thoracic=== In addition to the problems found in lower-level injuries, thoracic (chest height) spinal lesions can affect the muscles in the trunk. Injuries at the level of T1 to T8 result in inability to control the abdominal muscles. Trunk stability may be affected; even more so in higher level injuries.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|pp=311, 313}} The lower the level of injury, the less extensive its effects. Injuries from T9 to T12 result in partial loss of trunk and abdominal muscle control. Thoracic spinal injuries result in [[paraplegia]], but function of the hands, arms, and neck are not affected.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=311}}
<!--AUTONOMIC DYSREFLEXIA--> One condition that occurs typically in lesions above the T6 level is [[autonomic dysreflexia]] (AD), in which the blood pressure increases to dangerous levels, high enough to cause potentially deadly [[stroke]].{{sfn|Cifu|Lew|2013|p=197}}<ref name="Dimitriadis10"/> It results from an overreaction of the system to a stimulus such as pain below the level of injury, because inhibitory signals from the brain cannot pass the lesion to dampen the excitatory [[sympathetic nervous system]] response.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}} Signs and symptoms of AD include anxiety, [[headache]], [[nausea]], [[tinnitus|ringing in the ears]], blurred vision, flushed skin, and [[nasal congestion]].{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}} It can occur shortly after the injury or not until years later.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}}
Other autonomic functions may also be disrupted. For example, problems with body temperature regulation mostly occur in injuries at T8 and above.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=313}} <!--NEUROGENIC SHOCK--> Another serious complication that can result from lesions above T6 is [[neurogenic shock]], which results from an interruption in output from the [[sympathetic nervous system]] responsible for maintaining [[muscle tone]] in the blood vessels.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}}<ref name="Dimitriadis10"/> Without the sympathetic input, the vessels relax and dilate.{{sfn|Newman|Fleisher|Fink|2008|p=348}}<ref name="Dimitriadis10"/> Neurogenic shock presents with dangerously low blood pressure, [[bradycardia|low heart rate]], and blood pooling in the limbs—which results in insufficient blood flow to the spinal cord and potentially further damage to it.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=63}}
===Cervical=== Spinal cord injuries at the cervical (neck) level<!--, which account for almost 57% of spinal cord injuries, --> result in full or partial [[tetraplegia]] (also called quadriplegia).{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}} Depending on the specific location and severity of trauma, limited function may be retained. {| class="wikitable" style="width: 100%; float: right;" |+ Function after complete cervical spinal cord injury{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=843}} ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Level ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Motor Function ! style="text-align:left;background-color:#ffc0c0;" | Respiratory function |- |<!--col1-->C1–C4 |<!--col3-->Full paralysis of the limbs |<!--col3-->Cannot breathe without mechanical ventilation |- |C5 |Paralysis of the wrists, hands, and [[triceps brachii muscle|triceps]] |rowspan="3"|Difficulty coughing, may need help clearing secretions |- |C6 |Paralysis of the wrist flexors, triceps, and hands |- | C7–C8 |Some hand muscle weakness, difficulty grasping and releasing |}
Additional signs and symptoms of cervical injuries include low [[heart rate]], low [[blood pressure]], problems regulating [[body temperature]], and breathing dysfunction.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|pp=53–54}} If the injury is high enough in the neck to impair the muscles involved in breathing, the person may not be able to breathe without the help of an [[endotracheal tube]] and mechanical ventilator.<ref name="NINDS13"/>
===Complications===
Complications of spinal cord injuries include [[pulmonary edema]], [[respiratory failure]], [[neurogenic shock]], and [[paralysis]] below the injury site.
<!--MUSCULOSKELETAL--> In the long term, the loss of muscle function can have additional effects from disuse, including [[atrophy]] of the muscle. Immobility can lead to [[pressure sore]]s, particularly in bony areas, requiring precautions such as extra cushioning and turning in bed every two hours (in the acute setting) to relieve pressure.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=70}} In the long term, people in wheelchairs must shift periodically to relieve pressure.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=314–15}} Another complication is pain, including [[nociceptive pain]] (indication of potential or actual tissue damage) and [[neuropathic pain]], when nerves affected by damage convey erroneous pain signals in the absence of noxious stimuli.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=17}} [[Spasticity]], the uncontrollable tensing of muscles below the level of injury, occurs in 65–78% of chronic SCI.<ref name="Hesse12"/> It results from lack of input from the brain that quells muscle responses to stretch reflexes.<ref name="Selzer2010"/> It can be treated with drugs and physical therapy.<ref name="Selzer2010" /> Spasticity increases the risk of [[contracture]]s ([[Muscle contracture|shortening of muscles]], tendons, or ligaments that result from lack of use of a limb); this problem can be prevented by moving the limb through its full [[range of motion]] multiple times a day.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=315}} Another problem lack of mobility can cause is loss of bone density and changes in bone structure.{{sfn|Frontera|Silver|Rizzo|2014|p=407}}<ref name="Qin2010"/> Loss of bone density ([[Mineralization (biology)|bone demineralization]]), thought to be due to lack of input from weakened or paralysed muscles, can increase the risk of fractures.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=16}} Conversely, a poorly understood phenomenon is the overgrowth of bone tissue in soft tissue areas, called [[heterotopic ossification]].{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=15}} It occurs below the level of injury, possibly as a result of inflammation, and happens to a clinically significant extent in 27% of people.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=15}}
[[Image:1025 Atrophy.png|thumb|left|Muscle mass is reduced as muscles atrophy with disuse.]] <!--CARDIO & RESPIRATORY --> People with SCI are at especially high risk for respiratory and cardiovascular problems, so hospital staff must be watchful to avoid them.<ref name="Fehlings11"/> Respiratory problems (especially pneumonia) are the leading cause of death in people with SCI, followed by infections, usually of pressure sores, [[urinary tract infection]]s and [[respiratory infection]]s.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=26}} [[Pneumonia]] can be accompanied by [[shortness of breath]], fever, and anxiety.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}}
<!--DVT--> Another potentially deadly threat to respiration is [[deep venous thrombosis]] (DVT), in which blood forms a clot in immobile limbs; the clot can break off and form a [[pulmonary embolism]], lodging in the lung and cutting off blood supply to it.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=13}} DVT is an especially high risk in SCI, particularly within 10 days of injury, occurring in over 13% in the acute care setting.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=69}} Preventative measures include [[anticoagulant]]s, [[pressure hose]], and moving the patient's limbs.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=69}} The usual signs and symptoms of DVT and pulmonary embolism may be masked in SCI cases due to effects such as alterations in pain perception and nervous system functioning.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=69}}
<!--INFECTION--> Urinary tract infection (UTI) is another risk that may not display the usual symptoms (pain, urgency and frequency); it may instead be associated with worsened spasticity.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}} The risk of UTI, likely the most common complication in the long term, is heightened by use of indwelling [[urinary catheter]]s.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=70}} Catheterization may be necessary because SCI interferes with the bladder's ability to empty when it gets too full, which could trigger autonomic dysreflexia or damage the bladder permanently.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=70}} The use of [[intermittent catheterization]] to empty the bladder at regular intervals throughout the day has decreased the mortality due to kidney failure from UTI in the first world, but it is still a serious problem in developing countries.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=16}}
<!--DEPRESSION--> An estimated 24–45% of people with SCI suffer disorders of [[major depression|depression]], and the suicide rate is as much as six times that of the rest of the population.<ref name="BurnsMahalik2008"/> The risk of suicide is worst in the first five years after injury.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=27}} In young people with SCI, suicide is the leading cause of death.<ref name="Pollard07"/> Depression is associated with an increased risk of other complications such as UTI and pressure ulcers that occur more when self-care is neglected.<ref name="Pollard07"/>
==Causes== [[File:Man falling of horse.jpg|thumb|Falling as a part of recreational activities can cause spinal cord injuries.]]
Spinal cord injuries are most often caused by [[physical trauma]].{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=288}} Forces involved can be [[hyperflexion]] (forward movement of the head); [[hyperextension]] (backward movement); lateral stress (sideways movement); [[rotational force|rotation]] (twisting of the head); compression (force along the axis of the spine downward from the head or upward from the pelvis); or [[distraction injury|distraction]] (pulling apart of the vertebrae).{{sfn|Augustine|2011|p=198}} Traumatic SCI can result in [[contusion]], [[spinal cord compression|compression]], or stretch injury.<ref name="Sabapathy15"/> It is a major risk of many types of [[spinal fracture|vertebral fracture]].<ref name=radiologyassistant>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiologyassistant.nl/en/p54885e620ee46/spine-injury-tlics-classification.html|title=Spine injury - TLICS Classification|author=Clark West, Stefan Roosendaal, Joost Bot and Frank Smithuis|website=Radiology Assistant|accessdate=2017-10-26|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027025120/http://www.radiologyassistant.nl/en/p54885e620ee46/spine-injury-tlics-classification.html|archivedate=2017-10-27|df=}}</ref> Pre-existing asymptomatic congenital anomalies can cause major neurological deficits, such as [[hemiparesis]], to result from otherwise minor trauma.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kuchner|first=E. F.|last2=Anand|first2=A. K.|last3=Kaufman|first3=B. M.|date=1985-04-01|title=Cervical diastematomyelia: a case report with operative management|journal=Neurosurgery|volume=16|issue=4|pages=538–542|issn=0148-396X|pmid=3990933|doi=10.1097/00006123-198504000-00016}}</ref>
In the US, [[Motor vehicle accident]]s are the most common cause of SCIs; second are [[Falling (accident)|falls]], then violence such as gunshot wounds, then [[sports injury|sports injuries]].{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|pp=24–25}} In some countries falls are more common, even surpassing vehicle crashes as the leading cause of SCI.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=10}} The rates of violence-related SCI depend heavily on place and time.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=10}} Of all sports-related SCIs, shallow water dives are the most common cause; [[winter sport]]s and [[water sport]]s have been increasing as causes while [[association football]] and [[trampoline]] injuries have been declining.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=34}} [[Hanging]] can cause injury to the cervical spine, as may occur in attempted [[suicide]].{{sfn|Brown|Wyatt|Illingworth|Clancy|2008|p=1132}} Military conflicts are another cause, and when they occur they are associated with increased rates of SCI.<ref name="Kabu15"/> Another potential cause of SCI is [[iatrogenic]] injury, caused by an improperly done medical procedure such as an injection into the spinal column.{{sfn|Frontera|Silver|Rizzo|2014|p=39}}
SCI can also be of a nontraumatic origin. Nontraumatic lesions cause anywhere from 30 to 80% of all SCI;<ref name="Scivoletto14"/> the percentage varies by locale, influenced by efforts to prevent trauma.<ref name="Celani01"/> Developed countries have higher percentages of SCI due to degenerative conditions and tumors than developing countries.<ref name="New14"/> In developed countries, the most common cause of nontraumatic SCI is degenerative diseases, followed by tumors; in many developing countries the leading cause is infection such as [[HIV]] and tuberculosis.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=24}} SCI may occur in intervertebral disc disease, and spinal cord vascular disease.<ref name="Van Den Berg10"/> Spontaneous bleeding can occur within or outside of the protective membranes that line the cord, and [[intervertebral disk]]s can herniate.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=5}} Damage can result from dysfunction of the blood vessels, as in [[arteriovenous malformation]], or when a blood clot becomes lodged in a blood vessel and cuts off blood supply to the cord.{{sfn|Fulk|Behrman|Schmitz|2013|p=890}} When systemic blood pressure drops, blood flow to the spinal cord may be reduced, potentially causing a loss of sensation and voluntary movement in the areas supplied by the affected level of the spinal cord.{{sfn|Moore|2006|pp=530–31}} Congenital conditions and [[tumor]]s that compress the cord can also cause SCI, as can vertebral [[spondylosis]] and [[ischemia]].<ref name="Sabapathy15"/> [[Multiple sclerosis]] is a disease that can damage the spinal cord, as can infectious or inflammatory conditions such as [[tuberculosis]], [[herpes zoster]] or [[herpes simplex]], [[meningitis]], [[myelitis]], and [[syphilis]].{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=5}}
==Prevention== Vehicle-related SCI is prevented with measures including societal and individual efforts to reduce [[driving under the influence]] of drugs or alcohol, [[distracted driving]], and [[drowsy driving]].{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=31}} Other efforts include increasing [[road safety]] (such as marking hazards and adding lighting) and vehicle safety, both to prevent accidents (such as routine maintenance and [[antilock brakes]]) and to mitigate the damage of crashes (such as head restraints, air bags, seat belts, and child safety seats).{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=31}} Falls can be prevented by making changes to the environment, such as nonslip materials and grab bars in bathtubs and showers, railings for stairs, child and safety gates for windows.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=32}} Gun-related injuries can be prevented with [[conflict resolution]] training, [[gun safety]] education campaigns, and changes to the technology of guns (such as [[trigger lock]]s) to improve their safety.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=32}} Sports injuries can be prevented with changes to sports rules and equipment to increase safety, and education campaigns to reduce risky practices such as diving into water of unknown depth or [[Spearing (gridiron football)|head-first tackling]] in association football.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=33}}
==Diagnosis==
{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=300 | align = right | image1 = Radiology ND 0127 AAL.jpg |width1 = 1982 | height1 = 2494 | image2 = C6-C7-disc-herniation-cevical-mri-scan-cropped.jpg |width2 = 726 | height2 = 900 | footer = X-rays (left) are more available, but can miss details like herniated disks that MRIs can show (right).{{sfn|Wyatt|Illingworth|Graham|Hogg|2012|p=384}} }} A person's presentation in context of trauma or non-traumatic background determines suspicion for a spinal cord injury. The features are namely paralysis, sensory loss, or both at any level. Other symptoms may include incontinence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nichd.nih.gov/health/topics/spinalinjury/conditioninfo/diagnosed|title=How is SCI diagnosed?|website=http://www.nichd.nih.gov/|language=en|access-date=2018-09-08}}</ref>
A radiographic evaluation using an [[X-ray]], [[X-ray computed tomography|CT]] scan, or [[MRI]] can determine if there is damage to the spinal column and where it is located.<ref name="NINDS13" /> X-rays are commonly available{{sfn|Wyatt|Illingworth|Graham|Hogg|2012|p=384}} and can detect instability or misalignment of the spinal column, but do not give very detailed images and can miss injuries to the spinal cord or displacement of [[denticulate ligaments|ligaments]] or disks that do not have accompanying spinal column damage.<ref name="NINDS13" /> Thus when X-ray findings are normal but SCI is still suspected due to pain or SCI symptoms, CT or MRI scans are used.{{sfn|Wyatt|Illingworth|Graham|Hogg|2012|p=384}} CT gives greater detail than X-rays, but exposes the patient to more [[radiation]],{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=78}} and it still does not give images of the spinal cord or ligaments; MRI shows body structures in the greatest detail.<ref name="NINDS13" /> Thus it is the standard for anyone who has neurological deficits found in SCI or is thought to have an unstable spinal column injury.{{sfn|DeKoning|2014|p=389}}
Neurological evaluations to help determine the degree of impairment are performed initially and repeatedly in the early stages of treatment; this determines the rate of improvement or deterioration and informs treatment and prognosis.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|pp=64–65}}{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=55}} The ASIA Impairment Scale outlined above is used to determine the level and severity of injury.<ref name="NINDS13"/>
==Management==
===Prehospital treatment=== [[Image:Immobilisation plan dur.png|thumb|Spine motion restriction with a long spine board]] The first stage in the management of a suspected spinal cord injury is geared toward [[basic life support]] and preventing further injury: maintaining airway, breathing, and circulation and restricting further motion of the spine.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=289}} <!--IMMOBILIZATION--> <!--MOI--> In the emergency setting, most people who has been subjected to forces strong enough to cause SCI are treated as though they have instability in the spinal column and have [[spinal motion restriction|spinal motion restricted]] to prevent damage to the spinal cord.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=38}} Injuries or fractures in the head, neck, or pelvis as well as penetrating trauma near the spine and falls from heights are assumed to be associated with an unstable spinal column until it is ruled out in the hospital.<ref name="NINDS13"/> High-speed vehicle crashes, sports injuries involving the head or neck, and diving injuries are other mechanisms that indicate a high SCI risk.{{sfn|Augustine|2011|p=207}} Since head and spinal trauma frequently coexist, anyone who is unconscious or has a lowered [[level of consciousness]] as a result of a head injury is spinal motion restricted.{{sfn|Cameron|Jelinek|Kelly|Brown|2014}}
<!--DEVICES--> A rigid [[cervical collar]] is applied to the neck, and the head is held with blocks on either side and the person is strapped to a [[Long spine board|backboard]].{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=38}} [[Kendrick Extrication Device|Extrication device]]s are used to move people without excessively moving the spine{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=37}} if they are still inside a vehicle or other confined space. The use of a cervical collar has been shown to increase mortality in people with penetrating trauma and is thus not routinely recommended in this group.<ref>{{cite journal|title=EMS spinal precautions and the use of the long backboard.|journal=Prehospital emergency care : official journal of the National Association of EMS Physicians and the National Association of State EMS Directors|date=2013|volume=17|issue=3|pages=392–3|doi=10.3109/10903127.2013.773115|pmid=23458580|url=http://www.naemsp.org/Documents/Position%20Papers/POSITION%20EMS%20Spinal%20Precautions%20and%20the%20Use%20of%20the%20Long%20Backboard.pdf}}</ref>
Modern trauma care includes a step called [[clearing the cervical spine]], ruling out spinal cord injury if the patient is fully conscious and not under the influence of drugs or alcohol, displays no neurological deficits, has no pain in the middle of the neck and no other painful injuries that could distract from neck pain.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=294}} If these are all absent, no spinal motion restriction is necessary.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=37}}
<!--DETERIORATION--> If an unstable spinal column injury is moved, damage may occur to the spinal cord.<ref name="ahn11"/> Between 3 and 25% of SCIs occur not at the time of the initial trauma but later during treatment or transport.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=289}} While some of this is due to the nature of the injury itself, particularly in the case of [[multiple trauma|multiple]] or massive trauma, some of it reflects the failure to adequately restrict motion of the spine. SCI can impair the body's ability to keep warm, so warming blankets may be needed.{{sfn|Cameron|Jelinek|2014}}
===Early hospital treatment=== Initial care in the hospital, as in the prehospital setting, aims to ensure adequate airway, breathing, cardiovascular function, and spinal motion restriction.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=53}} Imaging of the spine to determine the presence of a SCI may need to wait if emergency surgery is needed to stabilize other life-threatening injuries.{{sfn|Bigelow|Medzon|2011|p=173}} [[Acute (medicine)|Acute]] SCI merits treatment in an [[intensive care unit]], especially injuries to the cervical spinal cord.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=53}} People with SCI need repeated neurological assessments and treatment by neurosurgeons.{{sfn|DeKoning|2014|p=373}} People should be removed from the [[spine board]] as rapidly as possible to prevent complications from its use.<ref name=ITLS2018/>
<!--BLOOD PRESSURE--> If the [[systolic]] blood pressure falls below 90 [[mmHg]] within days of the injury, blood supply to the spinal cord may be reduced, resulting in further damage.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=63}} Thus it is important to maintain the blood pressure which may be done using [[intravenous fluids]] and [[vasopressor]]s.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|pp=63–64}} Vasopressors used include [[phenylephrine]], [[dopamine]], or [[norepinephrine]].<ref name=ATLS2018/> Mean [[arterial blood pressure]] is measured and kept at 85 to 90 mmHg for seven days after injury.<ref name="Witiw15"/> The treatment for [[hemorrhagic shock|shock from blood loss]] is different from that for [[neurogenic shock]], and could harm people with the latter type, so it is necessary to determine why someone is in shock.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|pp=63–64}} However it is also possible for both causes to exist at the same time.<ref name=ATLS2018/> Another important aspect of care is prevention of [[hypoxia (medical)|insufficient oxygen in the bloodstream]], which could deprive the spinal cord of oxygen.{{sfn|Bigelow|Medzon|2011|pp=167, 176}} People with cervical or high thoracic injuries may experience a dangerously [[bradycardia|slowed heart rate]]; treatment to speed it may include [[atropine]].<ref name=ATLS2018/>
<!--STEROIDS--> The [[corticosteroid]] medication [[methylprednisolone]] has been studied for use in SCI with the hope of limiting swelling and [[primary and secondary injury|secondary injury]].<ref name=Rou2017>{{cite journal|last1=Rouanet|first1=C|last2=Reges|first2=D|last3=Rocha|first3=E|last4=Gagliardi|first4=V|last5=Silva|first5=GS|title=Traumatic spinal cord injury: current concepts and treatment update.|journal=Arquivos de neuro-psiquiatria|date=June 2017|volume=75|issue=6|pages=387–393|doi=10.1590/0004-282X20170048|pmid=28658409}}</ref> As there does not appear to be long term benefits and the medication is associated with risks such as [[gastrointestinal bleeding]] and infection its use is not recommended as of 2018.<ref name=Rou2017/><ref name=ATLS2018/> Its use in [[traumatic brain injury]] is also not recommended.<ref name=ITLS2018>{{cite book|last1=Campbell|first1=John|title=International Trauma Life Support for Emergency Care Providers|date=2018|publisher=Pearson|isbn=9781292170848|edition= 8th Global |pages=221–248}}</ref>
<!--SURGERY--> Surgery may be necessary, e.g. to relieve excess pressure on the cord, to stabilize the spine, or to put vertebrae back in their proper place.<ref name="Witiw15"/> In cases involving instability or compression, failing to operate can lead to worsening of the condition.<ref name="Witiw15"/> Surgery is also necessary when something is pressing on the cord, such as bone fragments, blood, material from ligaments or [[intervertebral disc]]s,{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=65}} or a lodged object from a [[penetrating trauma|penetrating injury]].{{sfn|Wyatt|Illingworth|Graham|Hogg|2012|p=384}} Although the ideal timing of surgery is still debated, studies have found that earlier surgical intervention (within 24 hours of injury) is associated with better outcomes.<ref name="Witiw15"/><ref name="Liu15"/> Sometimes a patient has too many other injuries to be a surgical candidate this early.<ref name="Witiw15"/> Surgery is controversial because it has potential complications (such as infection), so in cases where it is not clearly needed (e.g. the cord is being compressed), doctors must decide whether to perform surgery based on aspects of the patient's condition and their own beliefs about its risks and benefits.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|pp=65–69}} {{anchor|traction}} In cases where a more conservative approach is chosen, [[bed rest]], cervical collars, motion restriction devices, and optionally [[Traction (orthopedics)|traction]] are used.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=67}} Surgeons may opt to put traction on the spine to remove pressure from the spinal cord by putting dislocated vertebrae back into alignment, but herniation of intervertebral disks may prevent this technique from relieving pressure.{{sfn|Bigelow|Medzon|2011|p=177}} ''Gardner-Wells tongs'' are one tool used to exert spinal traction to reduce a fracture or [[joint dislocation|dislocation]] and to reduce motion to the affected areas.<ref name="Krag89"/>
===Rehabilitation=== {{Main|Rehabilitation in spinal cord injury}} <!--REHAB TEAM--> SCI patients often require extended treatment in specialized spinal unit or an [[intensive care unit]].<ref name=review02/> The rehabilitation process typically begins in the acute care setting. Usually the inpatient phase lasts 8–12 weeks and then the outpatient rehabilitation phase lasts 3–12 months after that, followed by yearly medical and functional evaluation.{{sfn|Cifu|Lew|2013|p=197}} [[Physical therapist]]s, [[occupational therapist]]s, [[recreational therapist]]s, nurses, social workers, psychologists and other health care professionals work as a team under the coordination of a physiatrist<ref name="NINDS13"/> to decide on goals with the patient and develop a plan of discharge that is appropriate for the person’s condition.
[[File:Evo.JPG|thumb|left|Orthopedic devices such as [[ankle-foot orthosis|ankle-foot orthoses]] can aid in walking.]] In the acute phase physical therapists focus on the patient’s respiratory status, prevention of indirect complications (such as [[pressure ulcer]]s), maintaining [[range of motion]], and keeping available musculature active.<ref name="Fulk, G. 2007">{{cite book |author1=Fulk G |author2=Schmitz T |author3=Behrman A |year=2007 |contribution=Traumatic Spinal Cord Injury |editor=O'Sullivan S |editor2=Schmitz T |title=Physical Rehabilitation |edition= 5th |pages=937–96 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=F.A. Davis }}</ref>
<!--RESPIRATORY--> For people whose injuries are high enough to interfere with breathing, there is great emphasis on airway clearance during this stage of recovery.<ref name=Reid/> Weakness of respiratory muscles impairs the ability to cough effectively, allowing secretions to accumulate within the lungs.<ref name=Brown/> As SCI patients suffer from reduced [[total lung capacity]] and [[tidal volume]],<ref name="Winslow C"/> physical therapists teach them accessory breathing techniques (e.g. apical breathing, [[glossopharyngeal breathing]]) that typically are not taught to healthy individuals. Physical therapy treatment for airway clearance may include manual percussions and vibrations, [[postural drainage]],<ref name=Reid /> respiratory muscle training, and assisted cough techniques.<ref name=Brown /> Patients are taught to increase their intra-abdominal pressure by leaning forward to induce cough and clear mild secretions.<ref name=Brown /> The quad cough technique is done lying on the back with the therapist applying pressure on the abdomen in the rhythm of the cough to maximize expiratory flow and mobilize secretions.<ref name=Brown /> Manual abdominal compression is another technique used to increase expiratory flow which later improves coughing.<ref name=Reid /> Other techniques used to manage respiratory dysfunction include respiratory muscle pacing, use of a constricting abdominal binder, ventilator-assisted speech, and [[mechanical ventilation]].<ref name=Brown />
The amount of functional recovery and independence achieved in terms of activities of daily living, recreational activities, and employment is affected by the level and severity of injury.{{sfn|Weiss|2010|p=306}} The [[Functional Independence Measure]] (FIM) is an assessment tool that aims to evaluate the function of patients throughout the rehabilitation process following a spinal cord injury or other serious illness or injury.<ref name=Chumney/> It can track a patient's progress and degree of independence during rehabilitation.<ref name=Chumney/> People with SCI may need to use specialized devices and to make modifications to their environment in order to handle [[activities of daily living]] and to function independently. Weak joints can be stabilized with devices such as [[ankle-foot orthosis|ankle-foot orthoses]] (AFOs) and knee-AFOs, but walking may still require a lot of effort.<ref name="del-Ama12"/> Increasing activity will increase chances of recovery.<ref name="Frood, R. 2010"/>
==Prognosis== [[File:Holly Koester, 2007 Chevron Houston Marathon (357322273).jpg|thumb|Holly Koester incurred a spinal injury as a result of a motor vehicle collision and is now a [[wheelchair racer]].]]
Spinal cord injuries generally result in at least some [[incurable]] impairment even with the best possible treatment. The best predictor of prognosis is the level and completeness of injury, as measured by the ASIA impairment scale.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=293}} The neurological score at the initial evaluation done 72 hours after injury is the best predictor of how much function will return.<ref name="Scivoletto14"/> Most people with ASIA scores of A (complete injuries) do not have functional motor recovery, but improvement can occur.{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=293}}<ref name="Waters91"/> Most patients with incomplete injuries recover at least some function.<ref name="Waters91" /> Chances of recovering the ability to walk improve with each AIS grade found at the initial examination; e.g. an ASIA D score confers a better chance of walking than a score of C.<ref name="Scivoletto14"/> The symptoms of incomplete injuries can vary and it is difficult to make an accurate prediction of the outcome. A person with a mild, incomplete injury at the T5 vertebra will have a much better chance of using his or her legs than a person with a severe, complete injury at exactly the same place. Of the incomplete SCI syndromes, Brown-Séquard and central cord syndromes have the best prognosis for recovery and anterior cord syndrome has the worst.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=9}} <!-- NTSCI --> People with nontraumatic causes of SCI have been found to be less likely to suffer complete injuries and some complications such as pressure sores and deep vein thrombosis, and to have shorter hospital stays.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=5}} Their scores on functional tests were better than those of people with traumatic SCI upon hospital admission, but when they were tested upon discharge, those with traumatic SCI had improved such that both groups' results were the same.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=5}} In addition to the completeness and level of the injury, age and concurrent health problems affect the extent to which a person with SCI will be able to live independently and to walk.{{sfn|Cifu|Lew|2013|p=197}} However, in general people with injuries to L3 or below will likely be able to walk functionally, T10 and below to walk around the house with bracing, and C7 and below to live independently.{{sfn|Cifu|Lew|2013|p=197}}
<!--RATE OF RECOVERY--> One important predictor of motor recovery in an area is presence of sensation there, particularly pain perception.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=11}} Most motor recovery occurs in the first year post-injury, but modest improvements can continue for years; sensory recovery is more limited.{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=8}} Recovery is typically quickest during the first six months.<ref name="Recovery"/> [[Spinal shock]], in which reflexes are suppressed, occurs immediately after the injury and resolves largely within three months but continues resolving gradually for another 15.{{sfn|Cortois|Charvier|2015|p=236}}
<!--SEXUALITY--> [[Sexuality after spinal cord injury|Sexual dysfunction after spinal injury]] is common. Problems that can occur include [[erectile dysfunction]], [[anejaculation|loss of ability to ejaculate]], insufficient lubrication of the vagina, and reduced sensation and impaired ability to [[orgasm]].<ref name="Hesse12"/> Despite this, many people learn ways to adapt their sexual practices so they can lead satisfying sex lives.{{sfn|Elliott|2010}}
<!--MORTALITY--> Although life expectancy has improved with better care options, it is still not as good as the uninjured population. The higher the level of injury, and the more complete the injury, the greater the reduction in life expectancy.{{sfn|Fulk|Behrman|Schmitz|2013|p=890}} Mortality is very elevated within a year of injury.{{sfn|Fulk|Behrman|Schmitz|2013|p=890}}
==Epidemiology== {{Pie chart | thumb = right | caption = Breakdown of age at time of injury in the US from 1995–1999.<ref name="ProgressPromise">Data from the [[National Spinal Cord Injury Statistical Center]]. {{cite book|author1=Committee on Spinal Cord Injury|author2=Board on Neuroscience and Behavioral Health|author3=Institute of Medicine|title=Spinal Cord Injury: Progress, Promise, and Priorities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ewEJU8Sg-n8C&pg=PA57|date=27 July 2005|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-16520-4|page=15|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106031908/https://books.google.com/books?id=ewEJU8Sg-n8C&pg=PA57|archivedate=6 November 2017|df=}}</ref> | label1 = 0–15 | value1 = 3.0 | label2 =16–30 | value2 =42.1 | label3 =31–45 | value3 =28.1 | label4 =46–60 | value4 =15.1 | label5 =61–75 | value5 =8.5 | label6 =76+ | value6 =3.2 }} <!--INCIDENCE --> Worldwide, the [[incidence (epidemiology)|number of new cases]] since 1995 of SCI ranges from 10.4 to 83 people per million per year.<ref name="Witiw15"/> This wide range of numbers is probably partly due to differences among regions in whether and how injuries are reported.<ref name="Witiw15"/> In North America, about 39 people per every million incur SCI traumatically each year, and in Western Europe the incidence is 16 per million.<ref name="Liu15"/><ref name=Clement13/> In the United States, the incidence of spinal cord injury has been estimated to be about 40 cases per 1 million people per year or around 12,000 cases per year.<ref name=FSCIP/> In China, the incidence is approximately 60,000 per year.<ref name="Qiu09"/> <!--PREVALENCE--> The estimated [[prevalence (epidemiology)|number of people living with SCI]] in the world ranges from 236 to 4187 per million.<ref name="Witiw15"/> Estimates vary widely due to differences in how data are collected and what techniques are used to extrapolate the figures.<ref name="Singh14"/> Little information is available from Asia, and even less from Africa and South America.<ref name="Witiw15"/> In Western Europe the estimated prevalence is 300 per million people and in North America it is 853 per million.<ref name=Clement13/> It is estimated at 440 per million in Iran, 526 per million in Iceland, and 681 per million in Australia.<ref name="Singh14"/> In the United States there are between 225,000 and 296,000 individuals living with spinal cord injuries,{{sfn|Field-Fote|2009|p=3}} and different studies have estimated prevalences from 525 to 906 per million.<ref name="Singh14"/>
<!--ASSOCIATED TRAUMA--> SCI is present in about 2% of all cases of blunt force trauma.<ref name="ahn11"/> Anyone who has undergone force sufficient to cause a thoracic spinal injury is at high risk for other injuries also.{{sfn|Bigelow|Medzon|2011|p=173}} In 44% of SCI cases, [[multitrauma|other serious injuries]] are sustained at the same time; 14% of SCI patients also suffer [[head trauma]] or [[facial trauma]].{{sfn|Peitzman|Fabian|Rhodes|2012|p=288}} Other commonly associated injuries include [[chest trauma]], [[abdominal trauma]], [[pelvic fracture]]s, and long [[bone fracture]]s.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=55}}
<!--AGE & SEX--> Males account for four out of five traumatic spinal cord injuries.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}} Most of these injuries occur in men under 30 years of age.<ref name="NINDS13"/> The average age at the time of injury has slowly increased from about 29 years in the 1970s to 41.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2014|p=839}} Rates of injury are at their lowest in children, at their highest in the late teens to early twenties, then get progressively lower in older age groups; however rates may rise in the elderly.<ref name="DeVivo2012"/> In Sweden between 50 and 70% of all cases of SCI occur in people under 30, and 25% occur in those over 50.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=10}} While SCI rates are highest among people age 15–20,{{sfn|Pellock|Myer|2013|p=124}} fewer than 3% of SCIs occur in people under 15.{{sfn|Hammell|2013|p=274}} Neonatal SCI occurs in one in 60,000 births, e.g. from breech births or injuries by forceps.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=388}} The difference in rates between the sexes diminishes in injuries at age 3 and younger; the same number of girls are injured as boys, or possibly more.<ref name="SchottlerVogel2012"/> Another cause of pediatric injury is [[child abuse]] such as [[shaken baby syndrome]].{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=388}} For children, the most common cause of SCI (56%) is vehicle crashes.{{sfn|Augustine|2011|p=197}} High numbers of adolescent injuries are attributable in a large part to traffic accidents and sports injuries.<ref name="Aghayan14"/> For people over 65, falls are the most common cause of traumatic SCI.<ref name="Sabapathy15"/> The elderly and people with severe [[arthritis]] are at high risk for SCI because of defects in the spinal column.{{sfn|Augustine|2011|pp=197–98}} In nontraumatic SCI, the gender difference is smaller, the average age of occurrence is greater, and incomplete lesions are more common.<ref name="Scivoletto14"/>
==History== [[File:Edwin Smith Papyrus v2.jpg|thumb|right|The ancient Egyptian Edwin Smith Papyrus is the earliest known description of SCI.<ref name="Lifshutz04"/>]] SCI has been known to be devastating for millennia; the ancient Egyptian [[Edwin Smith Papyrus]] from 2500 BC, the first known description of the injury, says it is "not to be treated".<ref name="Lifshutz04"/> Hindu texts dating back to 1800 BC also mention SCI and describe traction techniques to straighten the spine.<ref name="Lifshutz04"/> The Greek physician [[Hippocrates]], born in the fifth century BC, described SCI in his [[Hippocratic Corpus]] and invented traction devices to straighten dislocated vertebrae.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|pp=3–4}} But it was not until [[Aulus Cornelius Celsus]], born 30 BC, noted that a cervical injury resulted in rapid death that the spinal cord itself was implicated in the condition.<ref name="Lifshutz04"/> In the second century AD the Greek physician Galen experimented on monkeys and reported that a horizontal cut through the spinal cord caused them to lose all sensation and motion below the level of the cut.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=5}} The seventh-century Greek physician [[Paul of Aegina]] described surgical techniques for treatment of broken vertebrae by removing bone fragments, as well as surgery to relieve pressure on the spine.<ref name="Lifshutz04"/> Little medical progress was made during the [[Middle Ages|Middle Ages in Europe]]; it was not until the [[Renaissance]] that the spine and nerves were accurately depicted in human anatomy drawings by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] and [[Andreas Vesalius]].{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=5}}
In 1762 a surgeon named [[Andre Louis]] removed a bullet from the lumbar spine of a patient, who regained motion in the legs.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=5}} In 1829 the surgeon [[Gilpin Smith]] performed a successful [[laminectomy]] that improved the patient's sensation.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=6}} However, the idea that SCI was untreatable remained predominant until the early 20th century.{{sfn|Morganti-Kossmann|Raghupathi|Maas|2012|p=229}} In 1934, the [[mortality rate]] in the first two years after injury was over 80%, mostly due to infections of the urinary tract and pressure sores.{{sfn|Fallah|Dance|Burns|2012|p=235}} It was not until the latter half of the century that breakthroughs in imaging, surgery, medical care, and rehabilitation medicine contributed to a substantial improvement in SCI care.{{sfn|Morganti-Kossmann|Raghupathi|Maas|2012|p=229}} The relative incidence of incomplete compared to complete injuries has improved since the mid-20th century, due mainly to the emphasis on faster and better initial care and stabilization of spinal cord injury patients.<ref name="Sekhon01"/> The creation of [[emergency medical services]] to professionally transport people to the hospital is given partial credit for an improvement in outcomes since the 1970s.{{sfn|Sabharwal|2013|p=35}} Improvements in care have been accompanied by increased life expectancy of people with SCI; survival times have improved by about 2000% since 1940.{{sfn|Holtz|Levi|2010|p=7}} IN 2015/2016 23% of people in nine spinal injury centres in England had their discharge delayed because of disputes about who should pay for the equipment they needed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Revealed: Patients stranded in hospital for months as officials 'squabble' over equipment|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/service-design/revealed-patients-stranded-in-hospital-for-months-as-officials-squabble-over-equipment/7021420.article|accessdate=15 February 2018|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=12 January 2018}}</ref>
==Research directions== {{main|Spinal cord injury research}}
Scientists are investigating various avenues for treatment of spinal cord injury. Therapeutic research is focused on two main areas: [[neuroprotection]] and [[neuroregeneration]].<ref name="Kabu15"/> The former seeks to prevent the harm that occurs from secondary injury in the minutes to weeks following the insult, and the latter aims to reconnect the broken circuits in the spinal cord to allow function to return.<ref name="Kabu15"/> Neuroprotective drugs target secondary injury effects including inflammation, damage by [[free radical]]s, [[excitotoxicity]] (neuronal damage by excessive [[glutamate]] signaling), and [[apoptosis]] (cell suicide).<ref name="Kabu15"/> Several potentially neuroprotective agents that target pathways like these are under investigation in human [[clinical trial]]s.<ref name="Kabu15"/>
[[File:Human bone marrow derived MSCs.jpg|thumb|left|Human bone marrow derived mesenchymal stem cells seen under phase contrast microscope (63 x magnification)]] [[Stem cell transplantation]] is an important avenue for SCI research: the goal is to replace lost spinal cord cells, allow reconnection in broken neural circuits by regrowing axons, and to create an environment in the tissues that is favorable to growth.<ref name="Kabu15"/> A key avenue of SCI research is research on [[stem cells]], which can [[cell differentiation|differentiate]] into other types of cells—including those lost after SCI.<ref name="Kabu15"/> Types of cells being researched for use in SCI include [[embryonic stem cell]]s, [[neural stem cell]]s, [[mesenchymal stem cell]]s, [[olfactory ensheathing cell]]s, [[Schwann cell]]s, activated [[macrophage]]s, and [[induced pluripotent stem cell]]s.<ref name="Silva14"/> Hundreds of [[stem cell research|stem cell studies]] have been done in humans, with promising but inconclusive results.<ref name="Aghayan14"/> An ongoing [[Phases of clinical research|Phase 2]] trial in 2016 presented data<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asteriasbiotherapeutics.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Wirth-ISCoS-14SEP2016-talk-FINAL.pdf|title=Initial Clinical Trials of hESC-Derived Oligodendrocyte Progenitor Cells in Subacute Spinal Cord Injury|last=Wirth|first=Edward|date=September 14, 2016|website=ISCoS Meeting presentation|publisher=Asterias Biotherapeutics|access-date=September 14, 2016|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921035451/http://asteriasbiotherapeutics.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/Wirth-ISCoS-14SEP2016-talk-FINAL.pdf|archivedate=September 21, 2016|df=}}</ref> showing that after 90 days, 2 out of 4 subjects had already improved two motor levels and had thus already achieved its [[Clinical endpoint|endpoint]] of 2/5 patients improving two levels within 6–12 months. Six-month data is expected in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asteriasbiotherapeutics.com/asterias-biotherapeutics-announces-positive-efficacy-data-in-patients-with-complete-cervical-spinal-cord-injuries-treated-with-ast-opc1/|title=Asterias Biotherapeutics Announces Positive Efficacy Data in Patients with Complete Cervical Spinal Cord Injuries Treated with AST-OPC1|website=asteriasbiotherapeutics.com|access-date=2016-09-15|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920155522/http://asteriasbiotherapeutics.com/asterias-biotherapeutics-announces-positive-efficacy-data-in-patients-with-complete-cervical-spinal-cord-injuries-treated-with-ast-opc1|archivedate=2016-09-20|df=}}</ref>
Another type of approach is tissue engineering, using [[biomaterial]]s to help scaffold and rebuild damaged tissues.<ref name="Kabu15"/> [[Biomaterials]] being investigated include natural substances such as [[collagen]] or [[agarose]] and synthetic ones like [[polymer]]s and [[nitrocellulose]].<ref name="Kabu15"/> They fall into two categories: [[hydrogel]]s and [[nanofiber]]s.<ref name="Kabu15"/> These materials can also be used as a vehicle for delivering gene therapy to tissues.<ref name="Kabu15"/>
One avenue being explored to allow paralyzed people to walk and to aid in rehabilitation of those with some walking ability is the use of wearable [[powered exoskeleton|powered robotic exoskeletons]].<ref name="Louie15"/> The devices, which have motorized joints, are put on over the legs and supply a source of power to move and walk.<ref name="Louie15"/> Several such devices are already available for sale, but investigation is still underway as to how they can be made more useful.<ref name="Louie15"/>
Preliminary studies of [[Spinal cord stimulator|epidural spinal cord stimulators]] for motor complete injuries have demonstrated some improvement.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Young|first1=W|title=Electrical stimulation and motor recovery.|journal=Cell transplantation|date=2015|volume=24|issue=3|pages=429–46|doi=10.3727/096368915X686904|pmid=25646771}}</ref>
